===Etymology 1===
{{etyl|enm}} {{term|plesen|plesen, plaisen|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|fro}} {{term|plaise|lang=fro}}, conjugated form of {{term|plaisir|lang=fro}} or {{term|plaire|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|la}} {{term|placeo|placēre|lang=la|to please, to seem good}}<ref name="dictionary">{{R:Dictionary.com}}</ref>, from the {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{recons|plā-k-||wide and flat|lang=ine-pro}}. Displaced native {{etyl|enm|-}} {{term|quemen|quemen, queamen|to please|lang=enm}} (from {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|cweman|cwēman|to please|lang=ang}}), {{etyl|enm|-}} {{term|biluvien||to please, delight|lang=enm}} (from {{etyl|enm|-}} {{term|be-|bi-, be-|lang=enm}} + {{term|luvien||to love|lang=enm}}), {{etyl|enm|-}} {{term|liken||to like, please|lang=enm}} (from {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|lician|līcian|to please, be like|lang=ang}}), {{etyl|enm|-}} {{term|lusten|lusten, listen|to be pleasing, delight|lang=enm}} (from {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|lystan||to please|lang=ang}}).

====Alternative forms====
* {{l|en|pleace}} {{qualifier|used from the Middle English period up to the 15th century, and in Scots until the 17th century}}

====Verb====
{{en-verb|pleas|ing}}

# {{transitive}} To make [[happy]] or [[satisfy]]; to give [[pleasure]].
#: ''Her presentation '''pleased''' the executives.''
# {{intransitive|ergative}} To [[desire]]; to [[will]]; to be pleased.
#: ''Just do as you '''please'''.''

